Actually, no: the break only happens when "0" is found. So if there's no zero, then we count all tokens and then break? No, we break only when we see "0". So without zero, we go through all tokens and then break? Actually, the break is inside the if. So without zero, we don't break and we count all tokens? The Java code:

            for (String str : input_array) {
                result += 1;
                if ("0".equals(str)) break;
            } So if we have tokens: [a0, a1, a2, ...] and the first zero is at position i, then result becomes i (and breaks). If there is no zero, then we go through all tokens and result becomes the number of tokens. Therefore, we must do the same. Steps in Fortran:

